<p><strong>Deer Mouse (<em>Peromyscus maniculatus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Cricetidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Peromyscus maniculatus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Deer Mouse<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Deer Mouse is 2⅘ inches in length, has a tail length of 2-5 inches, and weighs 18-35 grams. This mouse is widely distributed and the most variable of members of the genus. The color ranges from pale grayish buff to deep reddish brown. The tail is always sharply bicolored (white below and dark above). It is often difficult to distinguish between other species. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?shapeID=1039&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=37" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This mouse is found in nearly every dry-land habitat within its range. It is also found in grasslands and forests. It bears 3-5 young 2-4 times a year and gestation period is between 21-24 days. Its nests are found in underground burrows, tree, tree stumps, and buildings. It feeds on seeds, nuts, acorns, and insects, and stores remains. Its home range is ½-3 acres or more and its summer population is high with 10-15 mice per acre. These mice rarely live more than 2 years in the wild, and 5-8 years in captivity. Deer Mice droppings have been associated with certain human illnesses, such as hantavirus.</p>
